Our friend and former manager, John Tovar (on the right) sadly just passed away. (That’s Frank Callari on the left). Frank and John managed us (mavericks) in the very beginning. But before any of that and even before the Mavericks John was first and foremost my friend. He was already well known in the music scene (Miami) as the guy whose approval every young musician sought. If he was at your show, there was a reason. And that’s all it took. Soon thereafter others would follow. Then you’d get written up about in the local paper and so on, and so on…He was an influencer before we had iPhones, Facebook, and Instagram. He made things happen. Creative energy swirled around him even though he couldn’t sing a note or play a lick. The force was strong with him. Exactly because he didn’t play or even pretend to play he let his artists be artists. He respected what we did and he never wanted to change anyone. He simply wanted his artists to see themselves as artists and be the best version of that that they could be possibly be. He had this persona. But his persona belied his personality. The public saw a seemingly stoic giant of a man with the black cowboy hat standing in the back of the club or at the end of the bar. Never, ever upfront or upclose. Never. Always in black. Because of Johnny Cash! Jonny Cash! This is Miami. Nobody was that cool. That was the persona. Truth is that he was a deeply caring and loving individual with a wicked sense of humor. He loved music. He loved his friends, his artists. He expressed his undying love to at least two women that I know of. He died alone in his sleep. But he did not die unloved or unrecognized. He named the Mavericks. It all started with him. May he rest in peace…RM @thirtytigers @the_orchard_ @monomundorecordings @the_mavericks @norman.jacob @michaelalanreynolds @rudybikes1985 @thegreatbamdino @habanamenex
